{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}
{{Use South African English|date=May 2013}}

[[File:Kirsten Miller.jpg|frame|right|Kirsten Miller]]'''Kirsten Miller''' is a [[South Africa]]n novelist, writer and artist. Her '''first book''' ''Children on the Bridge: A Story of Autism in South Africa'' (ISBN 978-1770092099) is an autobiographical account of her work as a tutor of [[autism|autistic]] children. It details the challenges in dealing with these children and their families and the effect this work has on her personal life.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynews.co.za/index.php?fArticleId=3558846|author=Lindsay Ord - The Daily News|title=Entering their closed minds - Interview and Review}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citizen.co.za/index/article.aspx?pDesc=32305,1,22|author=Cathryn Pearman-Owens - The Citizen|title=Positive View - Review}}</ref>

Her '''novel''' ''All is Fish'' (ISBN 978-1770092181) was shortlisted for the 2005 '''European Union Literary Awards'''. The novel is set in the resort town of [[Mtunzini]] in [[KwaZulu-Natal|Zululand]], South Africa and deals warmly with the complex relationships between the three central protagonists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oulitnet.co.za/indaba/eu_winner.asp|author=Litnet|title=EU Literary Award: Jury Comments - Review}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.witness.co.za/default.asp?myAction=detail&myRef=54446&myCat=film|author=Janet van Eeden - The Natal Witness|title=Three childhood friends re-unite - Review}}</ref>

She has published '''short stories''' in 5 collections ("When the Master Calls", "The Chief's Spell", "White Boy", "Chance Encounter", "Only in Art" and "Mobile" published in ''Uncovered Mirrors, African Road'', ''African Compass'', ''Dinaane: Short Stories by South African Women'', ''New Writing in Africa'' and ''Africa Inside Out'', respectively), and was also a finalist 3 times in the SA Pen Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jacana.book.co.za/2007/08/31/kirsten-miller-renaissance-woman-adds-novelist-to-her-cv/|author=BOOK SA - Caroline|title=Kirsten Miller: Renaissance Woman}}</ref> In 2012 her autism themed '''play''' "Remember Joe" was published in ''Short, Sharp and Snappy'', a collection of plays by leading South African playwrights and authors.

Kristen has written an '''illustrated children's book''', "A Time for Fairies", which was published in South Africa in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atimeforfairies.co.za/author_illustrator.htm|author=A Time for Fairies|title=Website}}</ref>

Kirsten is a featured book reviewer for the [[Sunday Times]] and also contributes regularly to [[South African Airways]]'s inflight magazine ''Sawubona''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://reviews.book.co.za/blog/2009/05/11/kirsten-miller-reviews-to-heaven-by-water-by-justin-cartwright/|author=Kirsten Miller|title=Review Justin Cartwright's "To Heaven by Water"}}</ref>

Miller was featured in the 2008 ''Time of the Writer'' International Writers Festival alongside [[Breyten Breytenbach]], [[Charles Mungoshi]], [[Mauritian literature|Ananda Devi]] and [[John Pilger]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukzn.ac.za/cca/tow2008.htm|author=Centre for Creative Arts|title=2008 Time of the Writer}}</ref>

Kirsten Miller's '''artwork''' works in fabric, oils and watercolours, drawing inspiration from her surroundings and thoughts. Johannesburg's Unity Gallery has held a solo exhibitions of her work in 2005 and 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artthrob.co.za/05june/listings_gauteng.html|author=Artthrob|title=Guateng Listings}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unitydesign.co.za/gallery.html|author=Unity Design|title=Gallery}}</ref> Her fabric, beads and fibreglass commission of ''African Moo-nlight'' for [[CowParade]] was purchased on auction by the brewer [[SABMiller]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://southafrica.cowparade.com/cow/detail/2428/|author=CowParade South Africa|title=African Moo-nlight - Picture and Artist Bio}}</ref>

Miller has a BA (Hons.) ''[[cum laude]]'' from the [[UKZN|University of Natal]] and has held jobs as a university lecturer, creativity teacher and dolphin trainer. She has lived in London, [[Cape Town]] and [[Johannesburg]]. Kirsten currently lives in [[Durban]] and works with [[autism|autistic]] children as well as attending to her artwork and writing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kirstenmiller.co.za/index.html|author=Kirsten Miller|title=Homepage}}</ref>

